questions.explanation:
`this` is an implicit pointer available inside any non-static member function. It always points to the specific object on which the method was called.

```cpp
class Counter {
    int count;
public:
    void increment() {
        this->count++;  // same as count++
    }
};

Counter c;
c.increment(); // inside increment(), this == &c
```

Why the others are wrong:
- A) `this` is implicit ÔÇö you never declare it as a parameter.
- C) `this` exists in all non-static member functions, not just constructors.
- D) `this` points to the object instance, not to the class definition.

`this` is a pointer to the current object. Dereferencing it with `*this` gives the object itself. Returning it by reference (`Type&`) means the caller gets a reference to the same object ÔÇö no copy is made.

This is the standard pattern for the copy-assignment operator and enables **method chaining**:
```cpp
Vec& operator=(const Vec& other) {
    x = other.x;
    y = other.y;
    return *this; // return reference to self
}

// enables: a = b = c;
```

Why the others are wrong:
- A) `return *this` does not free memory ÔÇö `delete this` would (and is almost always wrong).
- C) Returning by value would create a copy; `return *this` in a `Type&` method does not.
- D) `this` points to the whole object, not just the first member.

