What is `player.points` after calling `reset`?
```cpp
struct Score { int points; };

void reset(Score s) { s.points = 0; }

int main() {
    Score player = {100};
    reset(player);
}
```

questions.explanation:
`reset` takes `Score s` **by value** ÔÇö a copy of `player` is made. Modifying `s.points` inside the function only affects the local copy. When `reset` returns, the copy is destroyed and `player` is unchanged.

```cpp
void reset(Score s) { s.points = 0; } // modifies the copy only

int main() {
    Score player = {100};
    reset(player);
    // player.points is still 100
}
```

To actually modify the original, pass by reference:
```cpp
void reset(Score& s) { s.points = 0; } // modifies the original
```

