What is wrong with this copy constructor?
```cpp
class Num {
public:
    Num(Num other) { /* ... */ }
};
```

questions.explanation:
A copy constructor must take its parameter **by reference** (`const Num&`). If it takes by value (`Num other`), the compiler must copy the argument to create the parameter ÔÇö which would call the copy constructor again, causing **infinite recursion**.

```cpp
// Wrong ÔÇö infinite recursion:
Num(Num other) { ... }

// Correct:
Num(const Num& other) { ... }
```

Why the others are wrong:
- A) Constructors must have the same name as the class ÔÇö that is intentional.
- B) This code will not compile ÔÇö most compilers reject it outright.
- D) Constructors never have a return type ÔÇö not even `void`.

questions.text:
What happens when `d = d` runs?
```cpp
class Data {
    int* arr;
public:
    Data(int n) { arr = new int[n]; }
    ~Data() { delete[] arr; }
    Data& operator=(const Data& other) {
        delete[] arr;
        arr = new int[5];
        for (int i = 0; i < 5; i++) arr[i] = other.arr[i];
        return *this;
    }
};

int main() { Data d(5); d = d; }
```

questions.explanation:
When `d = d` is called, `this` and `&other` point to the **same object**. The assignment operator first does `delete[] arr` ÔÇö which frees the memory. Then it tries to read `other.arr[i]` ÔÇö but `other.arr` is the same pointer that was just deleted. This is **undefined behavior** (use-after-free).

The fix is a **self-assignment guard**:
```cpp
Data& operator=(const Data& other) {
    if (this == &other) return *this; // guard
    delete[] arr;
    arr = new int[5];
    for (int i = 0; i < 5; i++) arr[i] = other.arr[i];
    return *this;
}
```
This is why the self-assignment check is mandatory in any raw-pointer assignment operator.

`operator<<` for stream output must be a **free function** (not a member) because `std::cout` is the left operand ÔÇö and you cannot add methods to `std::ostream`. Declaring it `friend` inside the class gives it access to private members.

```cpp
class Point {
    int x, y;
public:
    friend std::ostream& operator<<(std::ostream& os, const Point& p) {
        os << "(" << p.x << ", " << p.y << ")";
        return os; // enables chaining: cout << p1 << p2
    }
};
```

Why the others are wrong:
- A) Returns `void` ÔÇö cannot chain `cout << p1 << p2`.
- B) `Point::operator<<` is a member function. Its left operand would be a `Point`, not `std::ostream`.
- D) Returns `Point&` instead of `std::ostream&` ÔÇö breaks chaining.

