What is the error?
```cpp
class Circle {
    double radius;
public:
    void Circle(double r) { radius = r; }
};
```

questions.explanation:
Constructors in C++ **never have a return type** ÔÇö not even `void`. Writing `void Circle(...)` turns it into a regular member function named `Circle`, not a constructor.

```cpp
// Wrong:
void Circle(double r) { radius = r; }

// Correct constructor:
Circle(double r) { radius = r; }
// or with initializer list:
Circle(double r) : radius(r) {}
```

Why the others are wrong:
- A) Constructors can absolutely have parameters.
- B) `this->radius` vs `radius` is a style choice, not an error here (the parameter name is `r`, not `radius`, so no ambiguity).
- C) Class-level initialization of member variables is optional and unrelated to this error.

questions.text:
What is the error?
```cpp
class Timer {
    int seconds;
public:
    Timer(int seconds) { seconds = seconds; }
};
```

questions.explanation:
Inside the constructor body, the name `seconds` refers to the **parameter** (it shadows the member). So `seconds = seconds` assigns the parameter to itself ÔÇö the member `this->seconds` is never set.

```cpp
Timer(int seconds) { seconds = seconds; } // parameter = parameter (noop)
```

Two correct fixes:
```cpp
// Fix 1: use this->
Timer(int seconds) { this->seconds = seconds; }

// Fix 2: use initializer list (preferred)
Timer(int seconds) : seconds(seconds) {}
// In the initializer list, left side = member, right side = parameter
```

This silent bug compiles without error ÔÇö the member stays uninitialized (garbage value). Always use initializer lists or `this->` to avoid name shadowing.

